<subSubSection id="7627F69D18F8D1052B6F68A0E2E4755B" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" type="taxonomical notes">
<paragraph id="8304D879D6C5C40CECA0AAA1FB3A124E" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Taxonomical notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6C691A34680CE613AFEBD4AB5EC071D5" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName id="E81C4074224F7954D7DD9E5158EEA3C4" class="Liliopsida" family="Commelinaceae" genus="Pontederia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pontederia sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis id="EE556030E09D9D3A00288867C6407E9A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">Pontederia sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a poorly circumscribed taxon that is morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName id="79E43250F45CCE2C45E57789E554ECA9" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. cordata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="cordata">
<emphasis id="D949B573A45DD415866D1DEC2E640D08" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. cordata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, due to the shape of the blade of their petiolate leaves. However, it is molecularly more closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="DECA1B7C2D891E9C53DD71ECD1E1FDA9" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. ovalis" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="ovalis">
<emphasis id="D71123A6F97B300B2DBB6DDFE0114CB7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. ovalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, having in common the anthocarp with sinuate ridges. The disjunctive distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="A64FB729514E88224F1DA8EBC7981B81" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis id="62E22F4AE72C0997375FE6AA51510544" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is probably related to misidentified specimens and/or the presence of cryptic species in what we currently accept as 
<taxonomicName id="9D9FBBF515884E00A4B551B6612AFEA4" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis id="6A7E415980F7A471873951A1CBEA141B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="4938531FEE812FF80CD92285E050C989" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">s.l.</emphasis>
Great variation in petiolate leaf shape can be observed throughout its distribution, especially in Brazil. We believe that 
<taxonomicName id="9EBD724FC4CB508F8252C494FCE43E65" family="Pontederiaceae" genus="P." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. sagittata" order="Commelinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="25" rank="species" species="sagittata">
<emphasis id="EC04431AEA38A0CFD7EAEA4D834FF0F3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="25">P. sagittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be properly studied, using different approaches than traditional taxonomy, in order to solve this issue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
